  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite being newly published in 2023, \"Contested Legacies\" has the potential to engage with contemporary discussions in its field, as suggested by its commercial linkage presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Contested Legacies,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2023, emerges as a significant contribution to ongoing academic discourse. While it currently has no citations, its commercial presence on notable platforms indicates a potential for wider public engagement and interest within scholarly communities. The book's availability on Amazon and Goodreads reflects its accessibility, positioning it as a resource that may resonate with both academic and lay audiences.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The inferred strength of the book's commercial linkage at 0.9 suggests that it is likely to attract attention as a resource for those exploring the complexities of contested legacies in various domains. The persistent relevance of the themes addressed within the book implies a significant opportunity for scholarly uptake, even in the absence of formal citations at this time.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the presence of a singular Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) association signifies its relevance to contemporary policy discussions. This connection highlights the potential for \"Contested Legacies\" to engage with sustainability and policy frameworks, enhancing its appeal to interdisciplinary audiences interested in the socio-political implications of legacy discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the landscape evolves, ongoing monitoring of the book's reception will be critical in understanding how it contributes to or influences future scholarly dialogue. Given its current trajectory, \"Contested Legacies\" stands poised to make an impact as both a scholarly text and a catalyst for broader conversations in the public sphere.</p>",
